- *May Thurner syndrome (iliac vein compression) integration* ([Chapter 10, new speculation @spec:mts-venous-return (cert 0.25); Chapter 14a, new venous outflow obstruction pathway in glymphatic section + new speculation @spec:venous-stasis-glymphatic (cert 0.35); Chapter 14k, new speculation @spec:mts-vascular-substrate (cert 0.25); references.bib, 8 new entries; Appendix H, new section `sec:bib-may-thurner` with 8 annotated entries; hypothesis registry, 3 new entries; hypotheses-trees/subtrees/may-thurner.md, new subtree with 13 nodes; hypotheses-trees/hypotheses-trees.md, root index updated; ops/plans/may-thurner-integration-plan.md, new plan; content-staging/may-thurner-literature-summary.md, Phase 1 literature review; content-staging/brainstorm-may-thurner-2026-05-27.md, Phase 3 brainstorm (120 ideas)]): Integration of May Thurner syndrome (iliac vein compression) as a potential mechanical/venous contributor to ME/CFS pathophysiology. Zero direct MTS-ME/CFS evidence exists in the literature; all integration is speculative. Anatomical prevalence 22--24% with female predominance 2--3:1 and diagnostic delay 4.2 years @Neglen2008MayThurnerReview @Ferreira2023VenousCompressionReview. Iliac vein stenting improves fatigue in 32--68% of MTS patients with SF-36 vitality gains of 19 points @Wolpert2020IliacStentingOutcomes @OSullivan2018StentingQoL. Key mechanistic chains: iliac compression → venous pooling → preload failure (Chapter 10); extracranial venous obstruction → impaired cerebral venous return → glymphatic dysfunction → neuroinflammation (Chapter 14a). Hartung et al. demonstrated 36% IJV flow reduction upright in MTS vs 24% in controls @Hartung2019CerebralVenousReturn; Anderson et al. documented autonomic dysfunction in MTS with COMPASS-31 scores overlapping ME/CFS ranges @Anderson2021AutonomicDysfunction. Marshall et al. reviewed 3 ME/CFS studies finding abnormal cerebral venous return in 34--48% @Marshall2022CerebralVenousOI; Patel et al. linked venous stasis